ðŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, operators, variables aur constants ke saath, data ko manipulate karne ke liye use hoti hai. Operators, variable ko manipulate karne ke liye use hoti hai.

ðŸ“Œ C++ programming mein, operators ke kuch types hain. Yeh hain:

ðŸ“ 1: Arithmetic Operators: Yeh operators, arithmetic calculations ke liye use hai. Yeh hain: + (addition), - (subtraction), * (multiplication), / (division), % (modulus).

Example:

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;
    int c;

    c = a + b;
    std::cout << "Addition: " << c << std::endl;
    c = a - b;
    std::cout << "Subtraction: " << c << std::endl;
    c = a * b;
    std::cout << "Multiplication: " << c << std::endl;
    c = a / b;
    std::cout << "Division: " << c << std::endl;
    c = a % b;
    std::cout << "Modulus: " << c << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

ðŸ“Œ Is example mein, arithmetic operators ke saath, arithmetic calculations ke liye use kiya gaya hai.

ðŸ“ 2: Relational Operators: Yeh operators, data ko compare karne ke liye use hai. Yeh hain: == (equal to), != (not equal to), < (less than), > (greater than), <= (less than or equal to), >= (greater than or equal to).

Example:

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;
    int c;

    c = (a == b);
    std::cout << "Equal to: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a != b);
    std::cout << "Not equal to: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a < b);
    std::cout << "Less than: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a > b);
    std::cout << "Greater than: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a <= b);
    std::cout << "Less than or equal to: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a >= b);
    std::cout << "Greater than or equal to: " << c << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

ðŸ“Œ Is example mein, relational operators ke saath, data ko compare kiya gaya hai.

ðŸ“ 3: Logical Operators: Yeh operators, data ko logical AND, OR aur NOT karne ke liye use hai. Yeh hain: && (logical AND), || (logical OR), ! (logical NOT).

Example:

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;
    int c;

    c = (a < b) && (a == 10);
    std::cout << "Logical AND: " << c << std::endl;
    c = (a < b) || (a == 20);
    std::cout << "Logical OR: " << c << std::endl;
    c = !(a < b);
    std::cout << "Logical NOT: " << c << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

ðŸ“Œ Is example mein, logical operators ke saath, data ko logical AND, OR aur NOT kar diya gaya hai.

ðŸ“ 4: Assignment Operators: Yeh operators, variable ko initialize aur assign karne ke liye use hai. Yeh hain: = (assignment), += (addition assignment), -= (subtraction assignment), *= (multiplication assignment), /= (division assignment), %= (modulus assignment).

Example:

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int a = 10;
    int b = 20;
    int c;

    c = a;
    std::cout << "Assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c += a;
    std::cout << "Addition assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c -= a;
    std::cout << "Subtraction assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c *= a;
    std::cout << "Multiplication assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c /= a;
    std::cout << "Division assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    c %= a;
    std::cout << "Modulus assignment: " << c << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

ðŸ“Œ Is example mein, assignment operators ke saath, variable ko initialize aur assign kiya gaya hai.


ðŸ“Œ Note: C++ programming mein, operators ke saath, variables aur constants ke saath, data ko manipulate kar sakte hai. Operators, variable ko manipulate karne ke liye use hoti hai.
